  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining the Dev Scripts**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the `package.json` file. Specifically, I\'m updating the `\"dev\"`, `\"build\"`, and `\"start\"` scripts according to React and Full-Stack guidelines. I\'m taking the full-stack route, and the adjustments involve adopting `tsx` for the development server. I\'m now making final adjustments to these commands.\n\n\n**Adding Server-Side Logic**\n\nI\'ve hit a snag, or rather, a missing piece! I need to create a `server.ts` file, as it wasn\'t in the initial file tree. Now, I\'m adapting the scripts in `package.json` to reflect this new server-side component. I\'m focusing on ensuring smooth integration with Vite and Express, and I\'ve verified that all necessary packages are in place. The main task now is crafting that `server.ts` file.\n\n\n**Analyzing Agent Control Center**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in the detailed requirements for the Shopify AI Agent Control Center, breaking down the SaaS dashboard and the Shopify store connection placeholder components. I\'m focusing on the connection status panel, summary statistics, and the approval queue. I\'m taking notes on the needed inputs, action buttons, and mock connected states, paying close attention to the `.myshopify.com` store URL and scope checkboxes.\n\n\n**Defining Agent Parameters**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the agent registry, specifically defining the parameters for several key agents. I\'m focusing on their roles, allowed tools, required Shopify scopes, and risk levels. I\'m currently defining the \"Store Setup Agent,\" the \"Content Agent,\" and the \"Analytics Agent\" and formalizing the details. I\'m taking extreme care to ensure that all agents can perform their functions correctly and safely.\n\n\n**Formalizing Agent Profiles**\n\nI\'m now detailing agents, including their system instructions, permitted tools, Shopify scope requirements, and risk levels. I\'ve documented the \"Inventory Agent,\" which uses `shopify.getOrders` and `shopify.getSalesSummary` with read permissions on orders and analytics. I\'ve also formalized the \"Theme Development Agent\" and \"Design Agent,\" both with high-risk scopes related to theme modification and read/write themes capabilities.\n\n\n**Defining New Agents**\n\nI\'m currently formalizing two more agents. I\'ve documented the \"Customer Support Agent,\" which uses `shopify.getOrders` and `shopify.getProducts` with low-risk scopes and the \"Media & Digital Agent,\" which uses `shopify.getProducts` and `shopify.prepareProductUpdate` with medium-risk scopes. Each agent has been assigned a risk level and can be enabled or disabled as needed.\n\n\\n\\n\n\n**Structuring Super Agent UI**\n\nI\'m now focused on the Super Agent user interface design. I\'m working to make it accept complex requests and integrate into the overall ecosystem. I\'m aiming for an interface that handles prompts like \"Write a high-converting optimized description for the Black Linen Shirt and draft it as an update\" or \"Check yesterday\'s sales figures and alert if we had issues.\"\n\n\n**Designing Super Agent Logic**\n\nI\'m now designing the logic for the Super Agent. The interface will be able to handle complex prompts like those described. Requests are directed to the server, which employs Gemini for dynamic routing or an intelligent rule-based orchestrator if the API key is unavailable. I\'m focusing on prompt classification, agent selection, tool invocation, mock data generation, and audit logging. Crucially, write tools now create a pending approval item with before/after comparisons for store owner review.\n\n\n**Abstracting Tool Interactions**\n\nI\'m now focusing on abstracting tool interactions with mock data generation to test the Super Agent. I\'m developing mock responses for `shopify.getShopInfo`, `shopify.getProducts`, `shopify.getOrders`, and `shopify.getSalesSummary`. Also, for `shopify.prepareProductUpdate`, I\'m configuring the return of \"queued\" status and approval payload creation. This allows me to simulate various API calls and tool behavior.\n\n\n**Defining Approval Mechanics**\n\nI\'m now focusing on two key aspects: `shopify.prepareThemePatch` and the approval queue. The theme patch tool, accepting `themeId` and `patch`, will return a \"queued\" status and generate an approval payload. This action triggers the approval queue. I\'m also now detailing the approval queue structure with its key data, and both approve and reject actions will log to the audit log.\n\n\n**Structuring Audit Logs**\n\nI\'m now detailing the audit log structure for the AI Agent Control Center. I\'m focusing on key fields like timestamp, initiator, event name, detailed descriptions, and a JSON data drawer for mock or real logs. I\'m also planning the agent detail page, with system instructions, tool permissions, and risk levels, all directly editable.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/types.ts` which will declare the common TypeScript types, interfaces, and enums for the Shopify AI Agent Control Center, covering store connections, agents, tool calls, approval queue items, and audit logs. This ensures clean type safety across both frontend and backend structures."
