    thinking: "**Building the Backend Server**\n\nI\'ve successfully created `types.ts`. Now, the backend server `server.ts` is next! The plan is an Express server. When not in production, it will be mounted with Vite middleware. I\'m also planning stateful mock data, specifically for the store connection which defaults to disconnected or connected.\n\n\n**Designing the Demo Store**\n\nI\'m now diving into the demo store design! I plan to let users interact with a simulated Shopify store (\"Luminary Essentials\"). They\'ll be able to toggle the connection, set a custom domain, and choose scopes, mimicking the Shopify OAuth process. I\'m also preparing seven agents, preloaded with instructions and tools, which users can customize and enable or disable. A mock Shopify DB will hold shop info, products, orders, and sales reports. Plus, an in-memory history of audit logs will be crucial.\n\n\n**Orchestrating API Requests**\n\nI\'m working on the `/api/orchestrate` route. It\'ll receive prompts and agent IDs. If a Gemini API key is available, I\'ll use `@google/genai` with `gemini-3.5-flash`. The system instruction will tell Gemini to act as a \"Super Agent Orchestrator\", with database info, agent details, instructions, and tools, to determine the optimal agent and tool for user requests. I\'ll seed the `approvalQueue` with 1-2 demo notifications for initial interaction. Also I am planning for `messages`, simulated logs, or orchestration traces.\n\n\n**Refining Orchestration Logic**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the fallback classifier for `/api/orchestrate`. Without a Gemini API key, it\'ll provide a deterministic mock brain. The fallback is triggered by keywords to trigger agents. This avoids crashes and allows for immediate demo use. I am now working on ensuring graceful handling of missing API keys, allowing the dev server to boot up without issues. The agents are designed to handle specific tasks and generate response chunks.\n\n\n**Defining Server Endpoints**\n\nI\'ve defined crucial server endpoints. These include routes for shop connection management, agent configuration, product and order retrieval, approval queue handling, audit log access, and orchestration control. I\'ve also incorporated a reset endpoint for easy mock data management and testing.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now create the master Express server file `server.ts`. This contains the in-memory store states (including Shopify credentials, 7 agent configurations, approval queue items, mock database items, and audit logs). It integrates real server-side Gemini queries using the official `@google/genai` SDK when `GEMINI_API_KEY` is present. If the API key is not yet set, it falls back to a deterministic rule-based classifier, ensuring the center is immediately responsive."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 958541274
    }
